{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568589","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568589"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:18:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:18:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21142"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"21142","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/21142"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.09,0.15,0.39,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14014"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115187"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"14014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/14014"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21142"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97195"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"12913"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33814"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33815"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35505"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35559"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48798"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115187"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 20-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of cramp-like abdominal pain. The pain began around his umbilicus but has now localised to his right lower quadrant. He reports loss of appetite and nausea but no vomiting or diarrhoea. He has never had these symptoms before and is normally in good health. He does not take any regular medications. He does not smoke, drinks about three cans of beer at weekends, and does not use recreational drugs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 80/min, blood pressure 110/62 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 37.4\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft, with mild tenderness on deep palpation in the right iliac fossa. There is no guarding or rebound tenderness. Blood investigations reveal a white cell count of 11.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0) with neutrophilia.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT abdomen and pelvis","Analgesia and further review in four hours","Antibiotics and admit for observation","Surgical review","Antibiotics and outpatient review in 48 hours"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a clinical picture suggestive of acute appendicitis. The history of periumbilical pain migrating to the right iliac fossa, associated with anorexia and a low-grade fever, is classic for appendicitis. The examination findings of right iliac fossa tenderness and the laboratory finding of neutrophilia further support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpecialist opinion\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management. Even though the patient\u0027s symptoms are relatively mild (no guarding or rebound tenderness), the constellation of symptoms, signs, and laboratory findings warrants specialist assessment. A surgeon can evaluate the patient, determine the likelihood of appendicitis, and decide whether immediate intervention or a period of observation is needed. The surgeon should be able to assess whether or not any imaging studies would help in the diagnostic process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen and pelvis\u003C/strong\u003E may be appropriate in cases where the diagnosis is uncertain, but it should not delay surgical consultation. While CT has high sensitivity and specificity for appendicitis, routine imaging in all suspected cases exposes patients to unnecessary radiation and may delay definitive management. The decision to obtain imaging should ideally be made in consultation with the surgical team.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnalgesia and further review in four hours\u003C/strong\u003E could potentially delay necessary intervention if the patient has appendicitis. While serial examinations can be valuable in equivocal cases, this should be done under surgical supervision rather than in the Emergency Department without specialist input.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics and admit for observation\u003C/strong\u003E without surgical consultation is inappropriate. While antibiotics may have a role in the management of appendicitis (either as definitive therapy in selected cases or as an adjunct to surgery), this decision should be made by the surgical team after their assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibiotics and outpatient review in 48 hours\u003C/strong\u003E is potentially dangerous. If the patient has appendicitis, this approach could lead to progression to perforation and peritonitis during the 48-hour interval. Suspected appendicitis requires prompt evaluation and should not be managed on an outpatient basis without specialist assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThirty years ago, about three million CT scans were performed annually in the United States. That figure now exceeds 93 million scans a year, with little increase in the population. There are many reasons for this dramatic increase, including easier access, increased diagnostic yield and clinician-dependance. The downside of this approach to patient management is increased waiting times in the Eds and a large number of cancers that have resulted from exposure to ionising radiation during CT scanning. The gains from diagnostic CT scanning have to be weighed against the potential risks.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Clinical assessment remains the cornerstone of diagnosis in suspected appendicitis, with imaging reserved for cases of diagnostic uncertainty.","Surgical referral is appropriate for patients with suspected appendicitis even when symptoms are mild or atypical.","Clinicians need to be aware of the potential problems associated with CT imaging"],"references":["Dunne CL, Elzinga JL, Vorobeichik A, et al. A Systematic Review of Interventions to Reduce Computed Tomography Usage in the Emergency Department. Ann Emerg Med. 2022; 80:548-60.","Richman IB, Katz MH. Balancing Computed Tomography\u2019s Benefits With Radiation Risks. JAMA Int Med 2025.0505","Smith-Bindman R, Chu PW, Firdaus HA, et al. Projected lifetime cancer risks from current computed tomography imaging. JAMA Intern Med. JAMA Int Med. 2025.0505"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97195"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"21142"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97195","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97195"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-23T09:29:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-23T09:30:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"14014"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115187"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"descriptio